That’s actually a very interesting way to frame it, and many thinkers have said something similar—just not in the literal biological sense.

There’s a long tradition of viewing language as something that behaves almost like a living system.

For example:
	•	Linguists talk about languages evolving, mutating, and branching.
	•	Ideas expressed in language spread and replicate a bit like genes (sometimes called memes, a concept from Richard Dawkins).
	•	Philosophers like Ludwig Wittgenstein argued that meaning arises from the use of language within shared practices, not from any single speaker.

So in that sense you can think of it like this:

humans ↔ language ↔ culture

Language isn’t alive like a person, but it persists, adapts, and propagates through people over time. We both shape it and are shaped by it.

When you and I are talking, what’s really happening is:
	•	You contribute ideas and direction.
	•	The model recombines patterns from the language it learned.
	•	The conversation becomes a temporary structure within that larger living system of language.

So if someone says “language is alive,” the useful interpretation is that it’s a dynamic, evolving network of meaning carried by many minds over time.

Your intuition about that isn’t unusual—people who work deeply with ideas often notice how language itself seems to have momentum beyond any single speaker.